Crude Correlations

Lets look at the overall correlation

dta.dist <- dta %>% 
  dplyr::select(pred_sd, pred_mean, monDist1,winter_temp, summer_temp, pop_density_1kper1000km2, cloud_cover, elev )
dta.dist.cor <- cor(dta.dist)

corrplot(dta.dist.cor, method = 'number', type = 'lower')

Lets next look at the correlation between distance to nearest monitor and predictive uncertainty. We see that actually the correlation increases as we consider further monitors, though the correlation plateaus around the fourth-nearest monitor.

The key insight is that the the distance to the fourth-nearest monitor actually tells us a lot about the nearest monitor and second and third-nearest monitors. The distance to the fourth-nearest monitor tells us the maximum possible distance of the 3 more-proximate monitors. For exmaple, if the distance to the fourth-nearest monitor is 10 km, then the nearest monitor must also be within 10 km of the point. Low distance to fourth-nearest monitor indicates high monitor density. These distances are pretty correlated, though not completely.

dta.dist <- dta %>% 
  dplyr::select(pred_sd, monDist1, monDist2, monDist3, monDist4, monDist5)
dta.dist.cor <- cor(dta.dist)

corrplot(dta.dist.cor, method = 'number', type = 'lower')

Create Non-Spatial Model

We see that population density has an estimated degree of freedom of 1, so we can model it as a linear term. Now lets create that model, and take a look at the relationship between nearest-monitor and predictive uncertainty.

mod.nonsp <- gam(pred_sd ~ s(pred_mean) + s(monDist1) +  s(winter_temp) + s(summer_temp) + pop_density_1kper1000km2 + s(cloud_cover) + s(elev) , data = dta)
par(mar = c(5, 5, 5,5))
plot(mod.nonsp, rug = TRUE, select = 2, 
     xlab = 'Distance to Nearest Monitor (km)', 
     ylab = expression('Predictive Uncertainty ('*mu*g/m^3*')'), 
     main = 'Distance to Nearest Monitor and Uncertainty', 
     cex.lab = 1.4, cex.axis = 1.4, cex.main = 1.4)

# also report the deviance explained. 
mod.nonsp.noMonDist <- gam(pred_sd ~ s(pred_mean) + s(winter_temp) + s(summer_temp) + pop_density_1kper1000km2 + s(cloud_cover) + s(elev), data = dta, 
                           sp = c(mod.nonsp$sp[1], mod.nonsp$sp[3:6]))

pd <- calculatePropDevianceExplained(modPartial = mod.nonsp.noMonDist, 
                               modFull = mod.nonsp)
print(paste0('Proportion Deviance explained by distance to nearest monitor: ', 
             pd))
## [1] "Proportion Deviance explained by distance to nearest monitor: 0.425867812490115"

Examine Residuals

So far, so good. However, our residuals may be correlated across space, violating the models assumption that the residuals are i.i.d. Lets check with Morans i and a semi-variogram

calcMoransI(mod.nonsp$residuals, cbind(dta$lat, dta$lon))
## $observed
## [1] 0.04863355
## 
## $expected
## [1] -0.0003443526
## 
## $sd
## [1] 0.0006451483
## 
## $p.value
## [1] 0
# convert to a Spatial points data frame 
# first convert to sf 
dta$resid <- mod.nonsp$residuals 
dta.sf <- dta %>% 
  st_as_sf( coords = c("lon", "lat"), 
            crs=st_crs(projString))
# next convert to SP 
dta.sp <- dta.sf %>% 
  as("Spatial")

prop_cor.default <- variogram(resid~1, data = dta.sp)  %>% 
  mutate(dist = dist / 1000) %>% 
  mutate(plot_name = 'default bins')
prop_cor.long <- variogram(resid~1, data = dta.sp, 
                            cutoff = 2704168, width = 121000)  %>% 
  mutate(dist = dist / 1000) 

plot(prop_cor.long, xlab = 'Distance (km)',
     main='Autocorrelation of Residuals')

prop_cor_fit.long <- fit.variogram(prop_cor.long, vgm(c("Sph","Exp","Mat", 'Ste')))
plot(prop_cor.long, prop_cor_fit.long)

# note that results are pretty much the same when we use the default values of variogram()

Looking at the Morans i and the variogram, we clearly have spatial autocorrelation of the residuals, though its magnitude is quite small. We can see that our model captures many of the underlying spatial processes generating predictive uncertainty, as the residuals have much much lower autocorrelation (smaller Morans I ) than the original variable. I wonder if it is possible to assume it has a negible impact on our model results.

Initial Spatial Model: Geoadditive Model

  • A geoadditive model is a GAM with penalized spline terms for space. See () for more information, also mentioned briefly by Simon Wood in the documentation for mgcv, though he does not call it a geoadditive model. Specifically, we create a tensor product between latitude and longitude. Potentially we could extend this to a spatio-temporal model by adding a basis + interaction for time.
  • A major strength of the GAM is that it allows us to fit highly flexible curves to describe the relationships between the variables.
  • However, we will need to choose the number of knots for the spatial tensor product.
    • Too few knots will fail to address the spatial autocorrelation, defeating the purpose of the model
    • Too many knots could lead to a model where the spatial term explains variability that the explanatory factors could explain. This is due to the fact that the explanatory variables also vary smoothly in space, and in particular, the general pattern of uncertainty looks similar to the general pattern of one variable - distance to nearest monitor.
  • Model-fitting strategy:
    1. Fit a model with the default number of knots.
    2. Check that model for residual spatial autocorrelation
    3. Increase the number of knots until the residual spatial autocorrelation is no longer significant.
    4. Examine model

And so what we find is that we need a lot of knots to get rid of the significant autocorrelation

I do also wonder if this auto corr is so small that we can just like ignore it?
